Subsidy Trap
Cambridge, USA — No policy is as directly at odds between good economics and good politics as food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies have become the core issue facing the three most important new world leaders. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
The subsidy cuts that Sisi faces are better than expected.
On the contrary, Modi faces a worse situation than expected, and it could even undermine the long-awaited WTO agreement.
While the situation facing Jokowi remains unclear.
In July, Sisi achieved what few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have managed: he significantly cut long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Surprisingly, there were almost no protests of opposition.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs more than $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained extremely low, often being used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often led to unrest, even toppling governments.
But Sisi's government seems to be able to make progress in this area.
Subsidies for bread have been cut by 13%.
Sisi has no choice.
Even after the subsidy reductions, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year still reached 10% of GDP (it would have reached 14% without the subsidy cuts).
But, almost no one anticipated that Sisi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, could act more swiftly than Modi. Modi won the prime ministership of India, where economic reform was urgently needed, through a decisive democratic majority.
In Indonesia, Jokowi inherited a long-standing fuel subsidy, amounting to as high as $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), which had already placed the country under heavy burden.
The outgoing Susilo had already taken a brave first step one year earlier by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors suggested reducing the remaining subsidies, and he himself candidly stated his plan to implement it gradually over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies, as agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive markets, the government — — rather than large private monopolies — — is the root cause.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
The controversy surrounding food and fossil fuel subsidies arises because they are often justified under the banners of environment or equality, but in reality, they fail to achieve these goals and often do more harm than good.
Less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies go to the poorest 20%, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the wealthiest.
Worldwide, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as evidenced by Modi's government that sought to protect agricultural subsidies.
In fact, Modi's government vetoed the WTO compromise, wiping out the most important progress in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies can sometimes benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in poor countries; and sometimes benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to do both.
As a result, India achieved a remarkable feat: it distributed wheat to consumers at artificially low prices, while at the same time experiencing overproduction, as farmers could receive high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs — — electricity, water, and fertilizers — — while the environment is damaged.
) The government purchased large quantities of corrupt rice and wheat, and the way consumers received only a small portion of the distribution was both corrupt and failed to help the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and procurement.
But it knows that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since it cannot permanently change these rules, Modi simply vetoed the trade promotion agreement (Trade Facilitation Agreement) that the WTO had been eagerly awaiting.
Once subsidies are implemented, it is difficult to withdraw them.
When global commodity prices rise (as they did in the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot isolate them from shocks.
But people accustomed to government-set food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong argument for not implementing subsidies from the beginning.
However, this does not mean that maintaining subsidies once they are implemented is necessarily the best choice for savvy politicians.
If the alternative to price hikes is shortages or rationing, angry opponents may also erupt.
Similarly, if the ever-widening gap eventually leads to even greater retail price increases, slow-moving leaders will also not benefit.
In an ideal scenario, when cutting food and energy subsidies, other more efficient measures to support low-income populations should be implemented simultaneously.
Developing countries have gained considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família conditional cash transfer policies, as well as India's Unique Identification system, an innovation in technological solutions.
However, some countries are forced to adjust only when a budget crisis hits, and they may not have the funds available for transfer payments to alleviate the pain.
Shrewd politicians might prefer to implement unpopular adjustments right at the beginning of their tenure.
Jokowi and Sisi both adopted this approach.
And Modi, who won the election with a landslide victory under the slogan of market reform, has fallen behind.
